<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO SPORTS ET CETERA: POINT LOMA CAPTURES GSAC CROSS COUNTRY TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Point Loma Nazarene College swept the first three positions and had four 
runners finish in the top eight to win Saturday's men's Golden State Athletic 
Conference Cross Country Championships for the third consecutive year at 
Bonelli Park in San Dimas. 
</P>
<P>
Sean O'Hara won the 8,000 meter race in 25 minutes 41.2 seconds, followed by 
Rick Penman (25:43.1) and Scott Lardner (25:43.7). PLNC finished with 27 
points; Fresno Pacific was second with 59, Azusa Pacific third with 68. 
</P>
<P>
PLNC's Gus Arce (26:31.9) took eighth. Robert Keter, Doug Ravasdy and Jim 
Michaelien were 13th, 14th and 16th. 
</P>
<P>
The PLNC women finished second to Westmont, 44-51. Anette Ronnerman (18:59) was 
fourth and Vanessa Couch (19:04) fifth for PLNC in the 5,000 meter race. 
</P>
<P>
San Diego State's Amy Peterson clocked 19:20 over 5,000 meters to win the 
University of San Diego Invitational at Morley Field. USD's Colleen McDonough 
(20:35) and Julie Lemery (21:19) finished sixth and eighth for the third-place 
Toreras. Christian Heritage's Heather Milner took 12th (22:05). USD's Max 
Lawson, 14th in 16:42, keyed a fourth-place finish for the men. 
</P>
<P>
WOMEN'S VOLLEYBALL 
</P>
<P>
UC San Diego swept Occidental, 15-8, 15-8, 15-3, to improve to 23-6 and 10-0 
against Division III opponents. Elizabeth Tan had nine kills and Dana Simone 
eight for UCSD, ranked No. 1 in Division III. Occidental fell to 14-10. 
</P>
<P>
PLNC defeated Christ College Irvine, 15-9, 15-3, 15-9, to remain unbeaten in 
eight GSAC matches. The Crusaders are 18-6 overall. Roberta Simpson had 11 
kills and Leanne Lopez had 35 assists for PLNC. 
</P>
<P>
U.S. International sophomore setter Jennifer Castillo, from Mt. Carmel, was 
named to the Mizuno Titan Classic all-tournmament team at Cal State Fullerton. 
The Gulls (7-16) lost to Cal Poly-San Luis Obispo, 12-15, 11-15, 15-13, 15-10, 
15-9, despite leading 12-3 in the third game. Stephanie Milbradt had 20 kills. 
USIU then defeated William and Mary, 15-6, 8-15, 12-15, 15-12, 15-11, behind 
Heather Kelley's 22 kills. 
</P>
<P>
MEN'S SOCCER 
</P>
<P>
The Sockers closed out preseason play with a 6-3 loss to the Stars at the 
Tacoma Dome. Paul Wright, Rod Castro and Keder scored for the defending indoor 
champions. Castro and David Banks had assists for the Sockers. 
</P>
<P>
The Sockers, 1-1 in preseason play, begin their Major Soccer League campaign 
Friday in Kansas City. The home opener is Nov. 2 against St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
Steve Cokkinis scored twice in the first half and PLNC made it stand up in a 
2-1 GSAC victory at Fresno Pacific. Cokkinis, who now has 10 goals, scored on 
assists by Dennis Vargas and Robert Romero. PLNC is 6-4-1, 3-1, Fresno Pacific 
5-8-1, 1-2. 
</P>
<P>
Christian Heritage goalie John Garretson had a school-record 20 saves, but it 
wasn't enough in a 6-1 loss to Westminster. Nathan Kingham scored the goal for 
Christian Heritage (2-5). 
</P>
<P>
WOMEN'S SOCCER 
</P>
<P>
Sandra Wright and Nicki Roche, both Santana High graduates, scored two goals 
apiece and Kelly Pietila added another as USIU scored a 5-0 victory over 
visiting Westmont College. Roche also had an assist for the Gulls (5-8-1). Lisa 
Ferragamo had two assists. Freshman goalie Amy Love posted her first shutout. 
Westmont is 1-8-2. 
</P>
<P>
Goalie Lorena Snyder's second straight shutout led SDSU (6-4-1) to a 2-0 
victory over UC Irvine. Laurie Christensen and Merris Welch scored for the 
Aztecs. 
</P>
<P>
WOMEN'S TENNIS 
</P>
<P>
Fifth-seeded Tonya Fuller of USD defeated Arizona State's Krista Amend 7-6 
(8-6), 4-6, 7-6 (6-4) to advance to today's finals of the Rolex ITCA Southern 
California Championships at UC Irvine. Fuller will play Arizona's Danielle 
Scott, the fourth seed, after she beat top-seeded Giovanna Carotenuto of USIU, 
6-0, 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
SDSU's Dorey Brandt and Nicole Storto advanced to the doubles finals after 
beating Cammie Foley and Iwalani McCalla of UCLA in the semifinals, 7-6 (8-6), 
6-3. Foley attended Bonita Vista High. 
</P>
