<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 15; Column 3; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
196 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Syracuse officials refused to allow a female student reporter to enter the 
locker room after Saturday's football game against Penn State and forced her to 
decide whether all other reporters also would be banned. 
</P>
<P>
Suzanne Yohannan, an assistant sports editor of the Daily Collegian, the Penn 
State student newspaper, said she was given the option shortly after Penn 
State's 27-21 victory. 
</P>
<P>
"I was approached by a Syracuse sports official who said that the players could 
be brought out of the locker room and the locker room itself would be closed to 
everyone, or the locker room would be open to all of the press except me," 
Yohannan said. 
</P>
<P>
She said felt pressured by the offer from Larry Kimball, sports information 
director at Syracuse. 
</P>
<P>
Yohannan, 21, a senior English major from Allentown, Pa., was accompanied by a 
male reporter from her newspaper, and he went into the locker room with other 
male reporters. 
</P>
<P>
Kimball said the university has a policy: "The locker room is either open to 
everybody or no one." 
</P>
<P>
But, he said, the team bans women. 
</P>
<P>
Penn State's locker room is closed to all reporters. Players are taken into a 
separate room for postgame interviews. 
</P>
</TEXT>
