<DOCNO> LA101490-0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 292851 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 14, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Real Estate; Part K; Page 2; Column 3; Real Estate Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
734 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA TRENDS: SACRAMENTO / BRADLEY INMAN; 
</P>
<P>
PETE WILSON, HOUSING ISSUES GO WAY BACK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BRADLEY INMAN, Inman is a syndicated real estate columnist. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pete Wilson isn't new to the housing issue. 
</P>
<P>
In 1970, as a member of the California Assembly, Wilson was called into Gov. 
Ronald Reagan's office and dressed down for his sponsorship of a major housing 
finance bill. 
</P>
<P>
Despite being asked to scrap his housing measure, Wilson shunned Reagan's 
advice and pushedforward with the bill, which was later defeated under pressure 
from the savings and loan lobby. 
</P>
<P>
Wilson has had varied experiences with the housing subject, which offers 
insight into what to expect from him if he is elected. 
</P>
<P>
"His understanding really goes deep," said private consultant and Wilson 
housing adviser Ward Connerly. He recalled a meeting Wilson hosted with several 
housing experts in which the San Diego Republican "was briefing us on what was 
going on in the housing market." 
</P>
<P>
He knows the issue from several different angles and sometimes conflicting 
perspectives. 
</P>
<P>
As a state legislator, he was a controversial champion of the housing cause. As 
mayor of San Diego, he pioneered growth management and was chastised as 
"anti-housing" by the building industry. 
</P>
<P>
In Sacramento as a lone housing voice in the Republican party, Wilson served as 
chairman of the Assembly's Urban Affairs and Housing Committee and pushed for 
more action at the state and local level on housing issues. 
</P>
<P>
He wrote a bill that requires all municipalities to prepare local housing 
plans. Wilson also pushed through legislation that said communities must 
establish public housing authorities and another measure that required the 
state to prepare statewide housing goals. 
</P>
<P>
Upon returning to San Diego as mayor in 1972, Wilson got involved with housing 
again -- not as its champion, however. He spearheaded one of the nation's first 
growth management schemes, and he was dubbed an enemy of housing by the 
building industry. 
</P>
<P>
In his state-of-the-city address in 1972, Wilson said, "the city, rather than 
the developer, will determine the timing and location of new development." 
</P>
<P>
At the time, Wilson was careful to defend his growth management proposal as 
sound fiscal policy. The city could not afford to extend city services to 
far-flung areas where development was being proposed, according to the Wilson 
growth management doctrine. 
</P>
<P>
In turn, Wilson pushed for more intensive development in the city's downtown 
core, where the infrastructure was already in place. 
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the housing industry had a fit. When Wilson pushed for a building 
moratorium in an area of San Diego called Mira Mesa, a crowd of construction 
workers picketed the San Diego City Council chambers. 
</P>
<P>
"Let's not forget that San Diego had a huge moratorium on building under Wilson 
and had the highest fees on housing in the state," said Barry Scherman, vice 
president of the Hofmann Co,. a San Francsico Bay-area homebuilder and whose 
senior officers have been supporting Feinstein. 
</P>
<P>
It wasn't until 1980 that a watered-down version of the Wilson growth 
management scheme was finally enacted. 
</P>
<P>
As it turned out, the plan did not forestall development in San Diego. The 
scheme called for an annual city growth rate of 9%, but the actual growth rate 
was 11% by the time Wilson was elected to the U.S. Senate in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
Growth control activists were so displeased with the boom in development that 
followed in later years that several ballot measures were proposed or approved 
that attempted to slow the pace of growth further in the San Diego area. 
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the growth management history in San Diego is a fundamental part 
of the Wilson legacy, as is his support for the California Coastal Protection 
Act, his opposition to Proposition 13 and his legislation that created the 
Governor's Office of Planning and Research, which established state guidelines 
for growth. 
</P>
<P>
But will growth and housing continue to be leading priorities if Wilson is 
elected governor? 
</P>
<P>
The Feinstein camp faults Wilson for not putting forth a detailed platform on 
housing and growth, which some say may indicate that Wilson won't make either 
issue a priority. 
</P>
<P>
The candidate promises that one of his top three issues will be "quality of 
life," which, according to Wilson's research director, Loren Kaye, embraces 
both housing affordability problems and growth management. 
</P>
<P>
"He understands the housing and growth issue and he's says that they are 
priorities," Connerly said. "So I expect him to be an activist governor working 
on these problems." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Series 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA101490-0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 292852 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 14, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Real Estate; Part K; Page 2; Column 3; Real Estate Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1350 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
AT HOME: HOUSES STAND WHERE ORCHARDS GREW; 
</P>
<P>
HACIENDA HEIGHTS: A GAS STATION AND MARKET WERE THE ONLY BUSINESSES 30 YEARS 
AGO. TODAY'S POPULATION IS SERVED BY SEVERAL SHOPPING CENTERS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARIAN BOND, Bond is a free-lance writer living in La Habra Heights. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thirty years ago, when Sandy and Jim Johnson moved to the area known as 
Hacienda Heights, it was a community of about 2,000 people, and the homes were 
nestled into orange, avocado and lemon groves. 
</P>
<P>
Jim Johnson had taken his first teaching position in Whittier -- just over the 
Puente Hills -- but the Johnson family was attracted to the rural environment 
of Hacienda Heights. 
</P>
<P>
However, Sandy recalls that at the time the only way to get to Whittier was 
over narrow and twisty Turnbull Canyon or narrow and twisty Hacienda Boulevard. 
</P>
<P>
"We had to go to Whittier to buy shoes. There was nothing but a gas station and 
a market in Hacienda Heights," she recalled. "There wasn't even a doctor's 
office, but we loved it like that. Our three children had the opportunity to 
grow up in the country." 
</P>
<P>
Today the Pomona Freeway borders the Los Angeles County community, there are a 
number of shopping areas and professional buildings along Hacienda Boulevard, 
and the groves have been replaced by houses in which a population estimated at 
60,000-plus now lives. 
</P>
<P>
The Johnson family has owned four homes in Hacienda Heights, but they've never 
been tempted to leave. Jim is director of child welfare and attendance in the 
Temple City school system. Sandy has been active in community affairs and is 
president of the Hacienda La Puente Unified School District. 
</P>
<P>
Sandy Johnson speaks proudly about the schools in Hacienda Heights and the 
community's ethnic diversity. 
</P>
<P>
The district offers the second largest adult education program in the state, 
second only to Los Angeles Unified, she said. 
</P>
<P>
On the ethnic mix, "We have about one-third Hispanic, one-third Asian and 
one-third Caucasian," Johnson said. "I'm out there all day working with 
families, students, teachers; I see many positives. This community has melded 
together very nicely." 
</P>
<P>
The community is rich in history. A part of the 49,000-acre land grant to 
William Workman and John Rowland by the last Mexican governor of California, 
the area still contains some of the original homes dating back to 1842. 
</P>
<P>
Dubbed North Whittier Heights about 1926, a community petition in 1961 changed 
the name to Hacienda Heights and a preliminary master plan was drafted by the 
Hacienda Heights Improvement Assn. While incorporation has been talked about 
over the years, it has never come to a vote. The improvement association 
continues to be active in the community and to offer a forum for residents. 
</P>
<P>
Maria and Richard Nunez have lived in Hacienda Heights for 13 years and have 
owned two homes. They paid $54,000 for their first house, and in 1988, they 
purchased their current 2,400 square foot pool residence for $250,000. 
</P>
<P>
"Six months after we bought this home we were offered $416,000 cash. We turned 
that down," Marla Nunez said. "We love our home." 
</P>
<P>
The Nunez family moved to Hacienda Heights from Los Angeles because of the 
location -- Richard works in Long Beach and they wanted the convenience -- and 
Maria liked the school system. Their three children are 15, 11 and 9 years of 
age. Maria is active in the community, in PTA, the improvement association and 
is president of the women's auxiliary for Little League. 
</P>
<P>
Also active in the community is Grace Kwok, co-owner of Century 21 Hacienda 
Estates. A realtor for 14 years in the community, Grace is president of the 
Hacienda Heights Chinese Assn. and often serves this growing ethnic component. 
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese people who live in Hacienda Heights are generally professional 
people," Kwok said, adding that in other communities where there is a 
significant Chinese population, they tend to be more commercially oriented. 
</P>
<P>
One reason the Chinese population has grown is that the Hsi Lai Temple -- the 
largest Buddhist temple in the United States -- was completed in November, 
1988. Located in the southern part of the area, on Glenmark Drive, just off 
Hacienda Boulevard, it encompasses 15 acres, and the buildings total 102,000 
square feet. 
</P>
<P>
People move to Hacienda Heights for many reasons, said realtor Donna Steinmetz: 
the schools, horse property, hills and trees, and there is the convenience of 
the freeway. There are three off-ramps into Hacienda Heights. 
</P>
<P>
The average listing price of a home in Hacienda Heights is $287,784, and the 
average sale price is $272,810, according to Marilyn McMullin, president of the 
Hacienda-Rowland-Diamond Bar Board of Realtors. 
</P>
<P>
Darlene Montes, a realtor with Century 21 Hacienda, said there is a wide price 
range of homes in the community. On the low end there are 900-square-foot, 
three-bedroom, one-bath homes built in the early 1950s that are listed for 
$150,000. 
</P>
<P>
In the $300,000 price range, there are homes of 1,500 to 1,800 square feet. For 
2,500 square feet, the price tag is going to be around $400,000. Much depends 
on the age of the home as well as the location. Custom homes are spread 
throughout the area. 
</P>
<P>
On the high end there is a listing for $1.85 million, another for $1.48 million 
and one at $1.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
These homes are often on 4 to 6 acres. They range from 4,000 to 6,000 square 
feet and feature game rooms, libraries, cedar closets, wet bars, saunas in 
master bedrooms. They have views, tennis courts and pools where the terrain 
permits. Generally, they are to be found in the Turnbull Canyon area on the 
western side of the community. 
</P>
<P>
Tigran Adhiwiyogo and his wife, Fay, moved with their two children into a 
2-year-old home in August, 1989. 
</P>
<P>
Originally from Indonesia, Adhiwiyogo had been transferred by his company to 
Southern California. His office is in Whittier, so they shopped for a home that 
would allow a short commute time and where there would be excellent schools. 
</P>
<P>
'We wanted a nice area to live in," he said. "We liked the quiet residential 
area we found in Hacienda Heights." 
</P>
<P>
He was surprised by the high price of real estate. They paid $525,000 for their 
3,000-square foot, four-bedroom 2 1/2-bath home with pool. "Our children have 
been active in all school activities, and have found friends quickly," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Luis and Juanita Cruz moved into their home on a quiet cul-de-sac last 
September. 
</P>
<P>
They were planning to buy a new home in Ontario when they stopped to visit 
friends in Hacienda Heights, and began to think that they might be able to 
afford something in the area. 
</P>
<P>
Luis is an evangelist who does a lot of traveling, and Juanita works in El 
Monte. She was not looking forward to a long commute from Ontario. 
</P>
<P>
The 1,800-square-foot house they purchased had a lot of deferred maintenance. 
Juanita was not at all impressed, but Luis felt there was the potential. They 
made an offer of $225,000, $50,000 below the asking price. 
</P>
<P>
"If she accepts that offer, it will be a miracle, and this house was meant for 
us," Juanita said. "She accepted it, and I think it was a miracle." 
</P>
<P>
Marilyn and Russell Ribb paid $25,000 for their house, but then they moved to 
Hacienda Heights 30 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
"It was avocado groves and lemon groves when we moved here," Marilyn Ribb said. 
</P>
<P>
The Ribbs raised three children in their home, and Russell was superintendent 
of schools at one time. The biggest change she notices aside from people and 
houses is that there is a lot more traffic to contend with. 
</P>
<P>
Lt. Dan Larson, assigned to the Industry Station of the Los Angeles County 
Sheriff's Department, said that traffic is one of their major concerns about 
Hacienda Heights, although they do experience residential burglaries and auto 
thefts. 
</P>
<P>
"A small portion of the area does have some gang-related activities, and 
inconsistent drug activity," he said. "It is not a high level." 
</P>
<P>
These are matters also of concern in the school district. Sandy Johnson said 
there has been a significant effort in educating the students and their parents 
in the dangers of gang and drug activities. "We work constantly on prevention," 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
